{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"35d6c6b5-e1b0-42bf-8486-39ee77b33864","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can tell you exactly what you need to configure to publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org.\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\nAdd these to your `MyMcpServer.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/repo</PackageProjectUrl>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n| Property | Why |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool` | Makes `dotnet pack` produce a tool package |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users will run (e.g. `my-mcp-server`) |\n| `OutputType=Exe` | Required — tools must be executables |\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### How users install & run it\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's the minimal setup. No special MCP-specific packaging is needed — the stdio transport just works since it reads stdin/writes stdout like any console app.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3f7a61df-9443-4203-93c4-8ed85e65eec2","outputTokens":496,"requestId":"7FCA:E24A4:454FB09:4BE766E:69F15B98"},"id":"7bf0a06d-7c2e-4e10-8ca4-45cba2f29d46","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:15:14.639Z","parentId":"bc8f2378-0454-4cd6-99f0-a204d276acbf"}
